{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A request whose signature does not match its body is rejected with a 401 response; the body is not forwarded.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is handler + signature verifier + forwarding boundary. A pure unit test of verifier logic can pass while request-wiring still forwards invalid events. Integration is sufficient because behavior text is about request validation/forwarding, not real network/OS conditions. Rejected System: no requirement for real HTTP timeouts/sockets; text only requires 401 and no enqueue.","test_description":"Run the webhook route in-process with real middleware/body parsing and a test queue adapter. Send a body with an intentionally wrong `X-Signature-256`; assert HTTP 401 and assert queue write was never called.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Assertions require module handoff correctness, not external infra.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"An event is written to the persistent queue before the HTTP 200 acknowledgment is returned to the sender.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This is an ordering guarantee across HTTP handler and persistence module. Mocking only one function risks missing handoff/await bugs. Integration with real queue persistence module (local DB/filesystem) catches real failure. Rejected System: behavior does not require real network/OS primitives beyond local module wiring.","test_description":"Use in-process HTTP app + real persistent queue implementation (test datastore). Instrument queue write completion timestamp and response completion timestamp; assert write completes first, then 200 is sent.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Test explicitly verifies cross-module sequencing, matching Integration floor.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The handler returns the HTTP response without waiting for downstream processing of the event to finish.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure appears when handler, queue, and downstream consumer interaction is wired incorrectly (e.g., awaiting worker completion). Integration is minimum to catch that orchestration bug. Rejected System: behavior text is about not waiting for downstream completion, not real OS/network behavior.","test_description":"Wire handler to queue + a downstream processor stub that blocks for a long duration. Send request and assert response returns quickly while processor is still running; later assert processing completes asynchronously.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Requires module interaction, not external infra.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The response arrives within 3 seconds wall-clock time even when downstream processing of earlier events is slow and concurrent.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is a wall-clock SLO under concurrency and backlog pressure. In-process fakes can hide event-loop starvation, scheduler effects, and real HTTP serving behavior. REAL-INFRA and MOCK-HIDE push to System. Rejected Integration: behavior explicitly says 'within 3 seconds wall-clock time' under concurrent slow load.","test_description":"Start the real service process, drive concurrent HTTP webhook traffic while earlier events are intentionally slow to process, and measure end-to-end response latency. Assert p100 (or strict per-request bound) stays under 3s for new incoming requests.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":"Needs real runtime timing/concurrency characteristics.","level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.13,"System":0.85,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"An event whose ID was already received is not written to the